The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, July 24, 2004 				 Wipro profit surges 73%
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								Bangalore, July 23: Wipro has reported a 73.21 per cent jump in net profit at Rs 357 crore for the first quarter ended June 30 compared with Rs 206.1 crore in the same period of 2003-04. 																								Riding on the back of the robust performance, the company has projected a revenue guidance of $318 million for the second quarter (July-September) from its global IT services business.																								Total revenue increased 48 per cent to Rs 1,769 crore in the quarter against Rs 1,198.9 crore in the same period of 2003-04. Revenues from global business at $300 million were more than the companys guidance of $292 million. Under the Indian GAAP, revenue from global IT services and products increased 45 per cent year-on-year to Rs 1,343.6 crore from Rs 925.5 crore.																								Consistent with our performance in recent quarters, every single vertical, every single geography and key service line has witnessed robust revenue growth, said Wipro chairman Azim Premji.																								The stock closed at Rs 529.25 on the Bombay Stock Exchange today, up from yesterdays close of Rs 524.15.																								The companys global IT services business continued to deliver consistent results with an 8.4 per cent sequential growth in revenues and higher operating margin of 27 per cent. Sequential growth of 8.4 per cent in revenues and expansion in operating margin for the fourth consecutive quarter were primarily the result of a sustained volume growth and an improving pricing environment, said vice-chairman Vivek Paul. Revenues from European clients recorded a 20 per cent sequential growth, he added.																								The companys research and development services witnessed a sharp rise in revenue, contributing 33 per cent to the total turnover, while the enterprise segment contributed 57 per cent; Spectramind contributed 10 per cent.																								Wipro Infotech saw a 68 per cent increase in revenue at Rs 270 crore, fuelled by growth in infrastructure management services, system integration, software solutions and consulting.																								Wipro posted higher operating margins from its global IT services business, primarily due to better price realisation in offshore and onsite projects. The company secured 35 new clients in IT services in the first quarter. Of this, 13 customers are for research and development services, 19 for enterprise services and three for IT-enabled services.																								The company hired 3,015 people during the quarter, taking its total headcount to 31,517 at the end of June. This included 20,768 engineers for IT services business and 10,749 for IT-enabled services. 																								Net addition during the quarter has been 1,566 people for IT services and 1,449 people for IT-enabled services, said Suresh Senapaty, corporate executive vice-president.																								Paul said the company raised wages by 15 to 18 per cent last year, but had not finalised the salary increases this year. It will be spread over the year and would be based on performance, he added.																								Wipro said it had hedged $998 million in forward contracts against foreign exchange fluctuations and accounted for contracts worth $227 in the first quarter results. 
